INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (194, 1, '2012-07-09 18:47:40', '2012-07-09 21:47:40', '<a href="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01560.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-126" title="Casa" src="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01560-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>\r\n\r\nDesde hace unos pocos días me vine a Bariloche. La versión 1 es sin perro, sin muebles, solo con el equipo de esquí de travesía y la notebook. Para la primera versión quería tener internet en la casa:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01604.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-127" title="Sin muebles" src="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01604-300x65.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="65" /></a>\r\n\r\ny hacer al menos una travesía con esquíes:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01599.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-128" title="by fair means" src="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01599-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>\r\n\r\nUna vez vi una charla de ted que contaba sobre la influencia de la arquitectura en la evolución de la música:\r\n\r\n<object width="526" height="374" classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0" bgcolor="#ffffff"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="always" /><param name="wmode" value="transparent" /><param name="bgColor" value="#ffffff" /><param name="flashvars" value="vu=http://video.ted.com/talk/stream/2010/Blank/DavidByrne_2010-320k.mp4&amp;su=http://images.ted.com/images/ted/tedindex/embed-posters/DavidByrne-2010.embed_thumbnail.jpg&amp;vw=512&amp;vh=288&amp;ap=0&amp;ti=883&amp;lang=en&amp;introDuration=15330&amp;adDuration=4000&amp;postAdDuration=830&amp;adKeys=talk=david_byrne_how_architecture_helped_music_evolve;year=2010;theme=the_creative_spark;theme=unconventional_explanations;theme=art_unusual;event=TED2010;tag=architecture;tag=arts;tag=future;tag=history;tag=music;&amp;preAdTag=tconf.ted/embed;tile=1;sz=512x288;" /><param name="src" value="http://video.ted.com/assets/player/swf/EmbedPlayer.swf" /><param name="pluginspace" value="http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer" /><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><embed width="526" height="374" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="http://video.ted.com/assets/player/swf/EmbedPlayer.swf" allowFullScreen="true" allowScriptAccess="always" wmode="transparent" bgColor="#ffffff" flashvars="vu=http://video.ted.com/talk/stream/2010/Blank/DavidByrne_2010-320k.mp4&amp;su=http://images.ted.com/images/ted/tedindex/embed-posters/DavidByrne-2010.embed_thumbnail.jpg&amp;vw=512&amp;vh=288&amp;ap=0&amp;ti=883&amp;lang=en&amp;introDuration=15330&amp;adDuration=4000&amp;postAdDuration=830&amp;adKeys=talk=david_byrne_how_architecture_helped_music_evolve;year=2010;theme=the_creative_spark;theme=unconventional_explanations;theme=art_unusual;event=TED2010;tag=architecture;tag=arts;tag=future;tag=history;tag=music;&amp;preAdTag=tconf.ted/embed;tile=1;sz=512x288;" pluginspace="http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer" allowfullscreen="true" allowscriptaccess="always" bgcolor="#ffffff" /></object>\r\n\r\nSi el entorno nos influencia, que nuevas posibilidades nos abre estar cerca de una ventana con vista a las montañas?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01569.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-129" title="Ventana" src="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/DSC01569-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>\r\n\r\nNo lo se, para mi es un experimento, uno en el que los amigos son bienvenidos.', 'Un lugar donde los amigos son bienvenidos', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '125-revision-6', '', '', '2012-07-09 18:47:40', '2012-07-09 21:47:40', '', 125, 'http://banquito.dev/125-revision-6/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (195, 1, '2012-07-23 22:18:15', '2012-07-24 01:18:15', 'Vía <a href="http://blog.kudewe.com/2012_02_01_archive.html" target="_blank">Fer Claverino</a>\r\n\r\nEl fin de semana pasado con mis amigos volvimos al pintoresco pueblo de <a href="http://blog.kudewe.com/2012/01/historias-de-alejandra-parte-1.html">Alejandra</a>. Al equipo original se sumaron Sole, que nuevamente nos ayudo a armar las actividades, nuestro amigo Clodo y el pana <a href="http://www.panchoalvarado.com/">Fran</a> de Ecuador.\r\n<a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Pwzi_XD7lfY/T0xD355PINI/AAAAAAAACfw/ni9jBR7wmYg/s1600/apertura.jpg"><img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5714016654939070674" class="aligncenter" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Pwzi_XD7lfY/T0xD355PINI/AAAAAAAACfw/ni9jBR7wmYg/s400/apertura.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a>\r\nEsta vez vinieron unas 15 personas, de distintas edades e intereses por la tecnología. Ademas de los tipicos juegos de apertura que hacemos para conectarnos, romper un poco el hielo y la timidez de algunos, esta vez propusimos 3 actividades para que los participantes elijan: periodismo, agua y ushahidi.\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>En la actividad de periodismo, guiada por Sabrina y Fran, los más grandes crearon un blog y publicaron contenido de su revista local (<a href="http://nuestrarevistaalejandra.wordpress.com/">Nuestra Revista</a>).</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-wNmtoLvH60Q/T0xESj7-C_I/AAAAAAAACf8/8c6zwd189uQ/s1600/periodismo.jpg"><img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5714017112901422066" class="aligncenter" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-wNmtoLvH60Q/T0xESj7-C_I/AAAAAAAACf8/8c6zwd189uQ/s400/periodismo.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\r\n<div>Los más chicos contaron nuevas historias de su pueblo y nos hablaron de la plaza, de la escuela y porque son importantes para ellos. Algo muy bueno fue que Leo (quien había venido la vez anterior) enseño como crear un post y subir fotos a otros chicos.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><a href="http://historiasdealejandra.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/escuela-dealejandra/">http://historiasdealejandra.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/escuela-dealejandra/</a></div>\r\n<div><a href="http://historiasdealejandra.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/parque-de-alejandra/">http://historiasdealejandra.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/parque-de-alejandra/</a></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Sole y Nico presentaron el problema del agua y la energía en Alejandra. Mediante un acertijo los chicos descubrieron que a veces, para encontrar la solución a un problema hay que hacer las preguntas correctas.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-3MOnTvXFqM8/T0xHzv2-NBI/AAAAAAAACgI/3VlT4w8dw90/s1600/agua.JPG"><img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5714020981572252690" class="aligncenter" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-3MOnTvXFqM8/T0xHzv2-NBI/AAAAAAAACgI/3VlT4w8dw90/s400/agua.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\r\n<div>y exploraron google buscando soluciones alternativas al problema.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Clodo y Nestor presentaron <a href="http://www.ushahidi.com/">Ushahidi</a>, una herramienta para reportar colaborativamente eventos en el tiempo y en un mapa. Con esta registraron algunos incendios ocurridos en Alejandra.</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ahd13-tFFbM/T0xJQ9HjHEI/AAAAAAAACgU/M3Wna1_L3Rk/s1600/ushahidi.JPG"><img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5714022582859275330" class="aligncenter" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ahd13-tFFbM/T0xJQ9HjHEI/AAAAAAAACgU/M3Wna1_L3Rk/s400/ushahidi.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\r\n<div>y luego los chicos nos contaron cómo lo hicieron en el blog</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://historiasdealejandra.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/como-acceder-al-ushahidi-de-alejandra/">http://historiasdealejandra.wordpress.com/2012/02/25/como-acceder-al-ushahidi-de-alejandra/</a></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Fue una tarde donde todos enseñamos algo y aprendimos algo. Alejandra es un pueblo muy lindo, con muchas cosas interesantes y con personas que vale la pena conocer.</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zSyiMceoJcI/T0xKGowKBMI/AAAAAAAACgg/NpApLAUXBLE/s1600/cierre.JPG"><img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5714023505105388738" class="aligncenter" src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-zSyiMceoJcI/T0xKGowKBMI/AAAAAAAACgg/NpApLAUXBLE/s400/cierre.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Queremos agradecer a todos los que nos ayudaron con esto, a la gente de la casa de la cultura, pero especialmente a Elena, la mamá de Nestor, que nuevamente nos recibió cálidamente en su casa y nos hizo sentir muy bien.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>Y que mejor forma de despedirse antes de empezar una travesía por los Alpes, no se me ocurre una mejor. Como dice Sebastian Álvaro, uno de los mejores exploradores de estos tiempos, tuve la suerte de armar equipo con buenos amigos, de esos con los que irías al fin del mundo.</div>\r\n<div><a href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-jspj0N_gcRM/T0xLsXYtpnI/AAAAAAAACgs/goEz7dh-UMo/s1600/amigos.JPG"><img id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5714025252790314610" class="aligncenter" src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-jspj0N_gcRM/T0xLsXYtpnI/AAAAAAAACgs/goEz7dh-UMo/s400/amigos.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>', 'Historias de Alejandra - parte 2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '160-revision-2', '', '', '2012-07-23 22:18:15', '2012-07-24 01:18:15', '', 160, 'http://banquito.dev/160-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (196, 1, '2012-08-11 16:24:28', '2012-08-11 19:24:28', 'Con la ayuda del gran <a href="http://www.guidoaccardo.com.ar">Guido Accardo</a> configuramos una instancia de EC2 para usar como servidor de desarrollo, staging, repositorios, wiki, etc etc. Como guia usamos el tutorial <a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2">EC2 Setup and  Usage</a> publicado en el curso <a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/">Engineering Long-Lasting Software: An Agile Approach Using SaaS and Cloud Computing (Alpha Edition)</a>. Planchamos un Ubuntu 12 Server de 64 bits y para crear nuevos usuarios (por defecto viene el user ubuntu) usamos esta guia: <a href="http://blog.sofasurfer.org/2011/07/16/ubuntu-ec2-add-new-admin-user/">http://blog.sofasurfer.org/2011/07/16/ubuntu-ec2-add-new-admin-user/</a>.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/aws.jpeg"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-200" title="aws" src="http://banquito.dev/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/aws.jpeg" alt="" width="260" height="95" /></a></p>\r\nEl pasos siguientes son:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Configurar ip pública con Elastic IP</li>\r\n	<li>Configurar Google Apps y subdominios.</li>\r\n	<li>Configurar VPN</li>\r\n	<li>Instalar y configurar <a href="http://moinmo.in/">MoinMoinWiki</a></li>\r\n	<li>Instalar SVN</li>\r\n	<li>LAMP, virtualenv, etc</li>\r\n	<li>Etc</li>\r\n	<li>Etc</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nEl futuro se pone bueno!', 'Configurando Amazon EC2', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'configurando-amazon-ec2', '', 'http://blog.sofasurfer.org/2011/07/16/ubuntu-ec2-add-new-admin-user/\nhttp://blog.sofasurfer.org/2011/07/16/ubuntu-ec2-add-new-admin-user/', '2012-08-11 16:28:31', '2012-08-11 19:28:31', '', 0, 'http://banquito.dev/?p=196', 0, 'post', '', 1) ; 
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (197, 1, '2012-08-11 15:55:54', '2012-08-11 18:55:54', 'El gran <a href="http://www.guidoaccardo.com.ar">Guido Accardo</a> nos ayudo a configurar una instancia de EC2 para usar como servidor de desarrollo, staging, repositorios, wiki, etc etc. Como guia usamos un tutorial que publicaron en el curso <a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/">Engineering Long-Lasting Software: An Agile Approach Using SaaS and Cloud Computing (Alpha Edition)</a>.\n<h2><span style="color: #ff0000; font-family: Arial;">Setting up your AWS account</span></h2>\n<div>\n<ol>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">If you don\'t have an AWS account already, go to </span> <a href="http://aws.amazon.com/">http://aws.amazon.com/</a> and click "Create Account" (the right of the page).  <em>You will need a valid credit card to create an account, though it will not be charged unless you exceed the $10 credit.  There is absolutely nothing we can do about this requirement.  </em><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/amazon-aws-and-github-credits-for-saas-students">See here for more details</a>.</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;">Redeem your account credit by visiting <a href="http://aws.amazon.com/awscredits/">http://aws.amazon.com/awscredits/</a>, entering the code we will email you, and clicking Redeem (you may be prompted to log in).</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;">Congratulations! You have now set up your AWS account.</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;">You will need a Secure Shell (ssh) client on your computer to connect to your instance.  Mac OS X and Linux already include the standard ssh command-line tool.  For Windows users we recommend installing the free <a href="http://www.putty.org/">PuTTY</a> application.</span></li>\n</ol>\n<div>\n<h2><a name="TOC-Setting-up-and-Launching-your-EC2-Instance"></a><span style="color: #ff0000; font-family: Arial;">Setting up and Launching your EC2 Instance</span></h2>\n<div><span style="font-family: Arial;"><strong>Note: There are two ways to set up your EC2 instance.   </strong></span>The rest of this page provides detailed information for the recommended approach. If you use the first approach (b<span style="font-family: Arial;">oth approaches are outlined </span><a href="http://bit.ly/aws-saas" rel="nofollow">here</a>), be sure that you have created your key pair in the same region as the region of the instance you choose.</div>\n<div>(Thanks to Shakil Langha and Jinesh Varia of Amazon for setting this up!)</div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Go to </span> <a href="http://aws.amazon.com/">http://aws.amazon.com/</a> and hover over "My Account/Console." Select "AWS Management Console" from the dropdown menu (you may be prompted to log in) .</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/awsconsole.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987448/ec2/awsconsole.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click on "EC2" in the bar at the top of the page.</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/ec2.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987449/ec2/ec2.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click "Region" under "Navigation" in the top left and select the region closest to you from the dropdown menu.</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/region.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331153397964/ec2/region.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click on "AMIs" under "Images" in the EC2 Dashboard at the left of the page.\n</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/images_amis.jpg?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987449/ec2/images_amis.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;">Enter the AMI ID corresponding to the geographic location closest to you (this should be consistent with the region you selected in step 3):</span>\n<ol>\n	<li>ami-3f9e4d56 : US East (N. Virginia)</li>\n	<li>ami-1a0a872a : US West (Oregon)</li>\n	<li>ami-09b3ea4c : US West (N. California)</li>\n	<li>ami-7b58610f : Europe (Ireland)</li>\n	<li>ami-9274ab8f : South America (Brazil)</li>\n	<li>ami-582c9a59 : Asia Pacific (Japan)</li>\n	<li>ami-9689cdc4 : Asia Pacific (Singapore)\n<div>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/chooseAMI.jpg?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331153479400/ec2/chooseAMI.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div>Be sure that you are viewing "All Images" and not "Owned By Me".</div>\n<div></div></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Right click on the bar showing the details of the AMI, and select "Launch Instance" from the dropdown menu.</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/launchinstance.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987449/ec2/launchinstance.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Leave Amazon\'s default settings (ie. 1 Micro Instance, not a Spot Instance), but choose an availability zone which is closest to your geographic location. (Note: if you find a micro instance is too small/slow, you may resize it to a Small instance while it is stopped- see "Using and Stopping your Instance" for more details.)</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/availzone.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987448/ec2/availzone.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Click "Continue" and do not change any of the default settings. Click "Continue" once more.</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/defaultReqinstances.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987448/ec2/defaultReqinstances.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Provide tags if you would like. These are not necessary, but may be helpful for you. Using "Name" in the "Key" field and a description of your instance in the "Value" field is helpful. Click "Continue."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/tags.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987449/ec2/tags.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Key Pairs:</span>\n<ol>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">If you have an existing AWS Key Pair, you may choose that option. </span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Otherwise, select "Create a new Key Pair" and provide a name for this key pair. Then click "Create &amp; Download your Key Pair." You will need to keep track of this file. It should have the form of &lt;name you provided&gt;.pem.</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Click "Continue."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/creatingDemo.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987448/ec2/creatingDemo.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div><strong>Note to Windows users: you will need to convert your key to something which PuTTY (the recommended Windows ssh program) can handle. Amazon provides instructions <a href="http://docs.amazonwebservices.com/AWSEC2/latest/GettingStartedGuide/ConnectToInstanceLinux.html">here</a>.</strong></div>\n<div><strong>\n</strong></div></li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Select the "default" security group (unless you have previously created a custom security group, this will be the only option). Click "Continue."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/defaultsec.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987448/ec2/defaultsec.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Click "Launch."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/launch.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987449/ec2/launch.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-family: Arial;">Congratulations! You have now launched your EC2 Instance!</span></li>\n</ol>\n<div>\n<h2><a name="TOC-Connecting-to-your-Instance"></a><span style="color: #ff0000; font-family: Arial;">Connecting to your Instance</span></h2>\n<div>\n<ol>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: Arial;">Go to </span> <a href="http://aws.amazon.com/">http://aws.amazon.com/</a> (you may be prompted to log in) and select EC2 if you are not already there.</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click on "Security Groups" under "Network &amp; Security."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/secgroups.jpg?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331212639360/ec2/secgroups.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Select the "default" security group (it will be your only security group if you have not already created one).</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/defsec.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331212947347/ec2/defsec.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">A panel providing information about the group will appear at the bottom of the page. Select "Inbound."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/inbound.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331212997200/ec2/inbound.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Select the menu to the right of "Create a new rule" and select "SSH."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/ssh.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331213092131/ec2/ssh.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click "Add Rule."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/sshtemp.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331213158458/ec2/sshtemp.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click "Apply Rule Changes."</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/applyrule.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331213210775/ec2/applyrule.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Click on "Instances" under "Instances" in the EC2 Dashboard at the left of the page.</span></span>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/instances_instances.jpg?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987449/ec2/instances_instances.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;">You will now see your instance and information regarding your instance.</span></li>\n	<li><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-size: medium;">Right click somewhere on the bar showing your instance information and select "Connect" from the dropdown menu.</span></span>\n<div></div>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/connect.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331138987448/ec2/connect.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div></li>\n</ol>\n<div><span style="font-size: medium;">You will log in to your instance in a way that allows you to run your browser (to connect to your SaaS apps) on your local computer.  In particular, we will set it up so that traffic directed to localhost:3000 (as described in Chapter 3 of ELLS) will be <em>forwarded</em> or <em>tunnelled</em> to port 3000 on your instance via the same connection you use for logging in.</span></div>\n<div><span style="font-size: medium;">\n</span></div>\n<div><span style="font-size: medium;">To connect with tunnelling <strong>on Mac OS X or Linux</strong>, type the following command in a terminal window, replacing <em>yourkey</em> with the filename of your keypair and <em>yourinstance</em> to the instance\'s name reported by AWS, such as </span><span style="font-size: medium;"><span style="font-family: \'courier new\', monospace;">ec2-99-99-99-99.compute-1.amazonaws.com :</span></span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>      ssh -L *:3000:localhost:3000 -i <span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><em>yourkey</em></span>.pem ubuntu@<span style="font-family: arial, sans-serif;"><em>yourinstance</em></span></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>(This means: "on the local side, take traffic destined to port 3000, forward it over the connection, and when it gets to the other side, send it to \'localhost:3000\' on that side.")</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>To connect with tunnelling using PuTTY for Windows, follow <a href="http://realprogrammers.com/how_to/set_up_an_ssh_tunnel_with_putty.html">these instructions</a>, using <span style="font-family: \'courier new\', monospace;">3000</span> as the Source Port and <span style="font-family: \'courier new\', monospace;">localhost:3000</span> as the destination (and of course, ignoring the part about running MySQL Administrator!)</div>\n<div><span style="font-family: Arial;">\n</span></div>\n<div><strong>You are now logged in to your instance!</strong></div>\n<h2><a name="TOC-Using-and-stopping-your-instance"></a><strong><span style="color: #ff0000;">Using and stopping your instance</span></strong></h2>\n<div>\n<div><strong>If you are using an EC2 AMI (or the VM), you do not need to run the configuration script; everything is already set up.</strong></div>\n<div>When you clone the homework 2 git repository, be sure to use the most up-to-date URI:</div>\n<div><span style="font-family: \'courier new\', monospace;">git clone git://github.com/saasbook/hw2_rottenpotatoes</span></div>\n<div>Follow the homework directions to set up your rottenpotatoes app.  You should now be able to use any web browser on your local computer to view your website, by connecting to http://localhost:3000.</div>\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>Don\'t forget to turn off your instance when you are done! Right click the instance in your AWS console and select "stop." You will need to restart your instance when you would like to use it again (by right clicking and selecting "start").</strong></div>\n<div><strong>\n</strong></div>\n<div>\n\n<strong><strong>Stop your instance:</strong></strong>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/stop.JPG?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331152774818/ec2/stop.JPG" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n</div>\n<div><strong>\n</strong></div>\n<div>\n\n<strong>Start your instance:</strong>\n<div><a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2/start.jpg?attredirects=0"><img src="http://beta.saasbook.info/_/rsrc/1331152834517/ec2/start.jpg" alt="" border="0" /></a></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>While your machine is stopped, you can also select "Change Instance Type" in order to increase your instance size to small (in case you found micro to be insufficient).</div>\n<div></div>\n</div>\n<div><strong>\n</strong></div>\n<div>When you are finished using your instance, you should use the Instance Actions menu on the AWS Management Console to stop it, so you don\'t continue to accumulate usage charges. If you <strong>STOP</strong> an instance, the instance goes away and you are no longer being charged for it, but the virtual disk connected to it persists, so you usually want this option. However, usage charges for persisting the disk will apply once you have exhausted the limits of the Free tier. If you <strong>TERMINATE</strong> an instance, the virtual disk connected to it is destroyed, and everything on it (including your work) is lost. Since the Free tier includes 750 compute-hours per month for a full year, you should probably not terminate the instance while taking this course. (Even if you do, though, you should be using Git and either GitHub or ProjectLocker to back up your important work to the cloud, as described in Appendix A of the book.)</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\nFuente: <a href="http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2">http://beta.saasbook.info/ec2</a>', 'Configurando Amazon EC2', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '196-revision', '', '', '2012-08-11 15:55:54', '2012-08-11 18:55:54', '', 196, 'http://banquito.dev/196-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ; 
